500
00:32:04,833 --> 00:32:07,426
Sit down if you want to.

501
00:32:07,501 --> 00:32:09,763
<i>I didn't know who I might meet</i>

502
00:32:09,835 --> 00:32:11,268
<i>or what they might ask.</i>

503
00:32:11,336 --> 00:32:14,099
You ever been
on a real shrimp boat?

504
00:32:14,171 --> 00:32:15,933
No.

505
00:32:16,005 --> 00:32:18,768
But I been on a real big boat.

506
00:32:18,841 --> 00:32:21,774
I'm talking about
a shrimp catching boat.

507
00:32:21,842 --> 00:32:24,776
I been working on
shrimp boats all my life.

508
00:32:24,844 --> 00:32:27,107
I started out
on my uncle's boat

509
00:32:27,178 --> 00:32:29,111
when I was about maybe 9.

510
00:32:29,179 --> 00:32:32,113
I was just looking
into buying my own boat

511
00:32:32,181 --> 00:32:34,114
and got drafted.

512
00:32:34,182 --> 00:32:37,446
My given name
is Benjamin Buford Blue.

513
00:32:37,518 --> 00:32:39,780
People call me Bubba,

514
00:32:39,852 --> 00:32:42,286
just like one of them
old redneck boys.

515
00:32:42,354 --> 00:32:43,615
Can you believe that?

516
00:32:43,687 --> 00:32:45,780
My name's Forrest Gump.

517
00:32:45,856 --> 00:32:48,119
People call me Forrest Gump.

518
00:32:48,190 --> 00:32:51,123
<i>So Bubba was from
Bayou La Batre, Alabama,</i>

519
00:32:51,191 --> 00:32:52,920
<i>and his mama cooked shrimp.</i>

520
00:32:54,894 --> 00:32:57,258
<i>And her mama
before her cooked shrimp,</i>

521
00:32:57,328 --> 00:33:00,921
<i>and her mama before her mama
cooked shrimp, too.</i>

522
00:33:00,996 --> 00:33:02,759
<i>Bubba's family knew everything</i>

523
00:33:02,831 --> 00:33:05,264
<i>there was to know about
the shrimping business.</i>

524
00:33:05,333 --> 00:33:07,596
I know everything
there is to know

525
00:33:07,667 --> 00:33:08,928
about the shrimping business.

526
00:33:09,001 --> 00:33:11,435
I'm going into
the shrimping business for myself

527
00:33:11,504 --> 00:33:13,766
after I get out of the army.

528
00:33:16,672 --> 00:33:17,661
O.K.

529
00:33:17,740 --> 00:33:19,000
Gump!

530
00:33:19,073 --> 00:33:21,667
What's your sole purpose
in this army?

531
00:33:21,742 --> 00:33:24,174
To do whatever you tell me,
Drill Sergeant!

532
00:33:24,243 --> 00:33:27,837
God damn it, Gump,
you're a goddamn genius.

533
00:33:27,912 --> 00:33:30,344
That's the most outstanding
answer I've ever heard.

534
00:33:30,412 --> 00:33:33,006
You must have
a goddamn I.Q. Of 160.

535
00:33:33,082 --> 00:33:35,674
You are goddamn gifted,
Private Gump.

536
00:33:36,917 --> 00:33:39,180
Listen up, people!

537
00:33:39,252 --> 00:33:42,185
<i>Now for some reason,
I fit in the army</i>

538
00:33:42,253 --> 00:33:44,187
<i>like one of them round pegs.</i>

539
00:33:44,255 --> 00:33:45,516
<i>It's not really hard.</i>

540
00:33:45,588 --> 00:33:47,521
<i>You just make your bed neat,</i>

541
00:33:47,589 --> 00:33:49,021
<i>remember to stand up straight,</i>

542
00:33:49,090 --> 00:33:50,682
<i>and always answer every question</i>

543
00:33:50,758 --> 00:33:52,690
<i>with "Yes, Drill Sergeant."</i>

544
00:33:52,758 --> 00:33:54,191
Is that clear?

545
00:33:54,260 --> 00:33:56,523
Yes, Drill Sergeant!

546
00:33:56,594 --> 00:34:00,028
What you do is drag your nets
along the bottom.

547
00:34:00,096 --> 00:34:01,358
On a good day,

548
00:34:01,430 --> 00:34:04,363
you can catch over
a hundred pounds of shrimp.

549
00:34:04,431 --> 00:34:05,693
Everything goes all right,

550
00:34:05,766 --> 00:34:07,528
2 men shrimping 10 hours,

551
00:34:07,600 --> 00:34:09,692
less what you spends on gas...

552
00:34:09,768 --> 00:34:11,860
Done, Drill Sergeant!

553
00:34:11,936 --> 00:34:13,369
Gump!

554
00:34:14,937 --> 00:34:17,871
Why did you put that weapon
together so quickly?

555
00:34:17,939 --> 00:34:19,873
You told me to, Drill Sergeant.

556
00:34:19,941 --> 00:34:21,531
Jesus H. Christ.

557
00:34:21,607 --> 00:34:23,541
This is a new company record.

558
00:34:23,609 --> 00:34:25,041
If it wasn't a waste

559
00:34:25,110 --> 00:34:26,542
of a fine enlisted man,

560
00:34:26,610 --> 00:34:29,043
I'd recommend you for O.C.S.,
Private Gump.

561
00:34:29,112 --> 00:34:31,376
You're going to be
a general someday!

562
00:34:31,447 --> 00:34:33,379
Now disassemble your weapon
and continue!

563
00:34:35,448 --> 00:34:37,382
Anyway, like I was saying,

564
00:34:37,449 --> 00:34:39,712
shrimp is the fruit of the sea.

565
00:34:39,784 --> 00:34:43,048
You can barbecue it,
boil it, broil it,

566
00:34:43,119 --> 00:34:44,552
bake it, sauté it.

567
00:34:44,620 --> 00:34:47,713
They's, uh, shrimp kabobs,
shrimp creole,

568
00:34:47,789 --> 00:34:51,723
shrimp gumbo,
pan fried, deep fried,

569
00:34:51,791 --> 00:34:53,053
stir fried.

570
00:34:53,126 --> 00:34:54,887
There's pineapple shrimp

571
00:34:54,959 --> 00:34:57,825
and lemon shrimp,
coconut shrimp,

572
00:34:57,894 --> 00:34:59,020
pepper shrimp,

573
00:34:59,095 --> 00:35:01,527
shrimp soup, shrimp stew,

574
00:35:01,596 --> 00:35:03,188
shrimp salad,

575
00:35:03,264 --> 00:35:05,026
shrimp in potatoes,

576
00:35:05,098 --> 00:35:06,530
shrimp burger,

577
00:35:06,599 --> 00:35:08,361
shrimp sandwich.

578
00:35:10,602 --> 00:35:12,693
That... That's about it.

579
00:35:16,939 --> 00:35:20,100
<i>Nighttime in the army
is a lonely time.</i>

580
00:35:20,173 --> 00:35:22,607
<i>We'd lay there in our bunks,</i>

581
00:35:22,676 --> 00:35:25,108
<i>and I'd miss my mama,</i>

582
00:35:25,176 --> 00:35:27,769
<i>and I'd miss Jenny.</i>

583
00:35:31,179 --> 00:35:33,113
Hey, Gump.

584
00:35:33,181 --> 00:35:35,773
Get a load of the tits on her.

585
00:35:48,522 --> 00:35:49,955
<i>Turns out...</i>

586
00:35:50,023 --> 00:35:52,114
<i>Jenny had gotten
into some trouble</i>

587
00:35:52,190 --> 00:35:55,455
<i>over some photos of her
in her college sweater.</i>

588
00:35:55,526 --> 00:35:57,720
<i>And she was
thrown out of school.</i>

589
00:35:57,794 --> 00:36:00,956
~ My baby does the hanky panky ~

590
00:36:01,029 --> 00:36:03,461
<i>But that wasn't a bad thing,</i>

591
00:36:03,530 --> 00:36:05,964
<i>'cause a man who owns a theater</i>

592
00:36:06,032 --> 00:36:07,464
<i>in Memphis, Tennessee,</i>

593
00:36:07,533 --> 00:36:09,124
<i>saw those photos</i>

594
00:36:09,200 --> 00:36:12,965
<i>and offered Jenny
a job singing in a show.</i>

595
00:36:13,036 --> 00:36:15,127
<i>The first chance I got,</i>

596
00:36:15,203 --> 00:36:17,466
<i>I took the bus up to Memphis</i>

597
00:36:17,538 --> 00:36:19,801
<i>to see her perform in that show.</i>

598
00:36:19,872 --> 00:36:21,304
That was Amber, Amber Flame.

599
00:36:21,373 --> 00:36:22,806
Give her a big hand.

600
00:36:22,874 --> 00:36:25,807
And now, for your listening
and viewing pleasure,

601
00:36:25,875 --> 00:36:27,638
direct from Hollywood,
California,

602
00:36:27,711 --> 00:36:29,473
our very own beatnik beauty.

603
00:36:29,545 --> 00:36:31,808
Let's give a big round of applause

604
00:36:31,879 --> 00:36:33,641
to the luscious Bobbie Dylan.

605
00:36:42,884 --> 00:36:48,650
~ How many roads
must a man walk down ~

606
00:36:48,722 --> 00:36:54,089
~ Before you can
call him a man? ~

607
00:36:54,157 --> 00:37:00,355
~ Yes, and how many seas
must the white dove sail ~

608
00:37:00,428 --> 00:37:02,361
<i>Her dream had come true.</i>

609
00:37:02,429 --> 00:37:04,363
~ Before she sleeps
in the sand? ~

610
00:37:04,431 --> 00:37:06,260
<i>She was a folksinger.</i>

611
00:37:06,331 --> 00:37:09,424
~ Yes, and how many times ~

612
00:37:09,500 --> 00:37:12,558
~ Must the cannonballs fly ~

613
00:37:12,635 --> 00:37:17,229
~ Before they're
forever banned? ~

614
00:37:17,304 --> 00:37:18,635
Shake it up now.

615
00:37:18,705 --> 00:37:20,137
Somebody get her a harmonica.

616
00:37:20,206 --> 00:37:21,935
~ The answer, my friend ~

617
00:37:22,008 --> 00:37:23,769
~ ls blowin' in the wind ~

618
00:37:23,841 --> 00:37:25,274
<i>This ain't Captain Kangaroo.</i>

619
00:37:25,342 --> 00:37:28,104
Hey, honey, I got
something here for you.

620
00:37:28,176 --> 00:37:30,235
Hey! God damn it!

621
00:37:30,311 --> 00:37:32,575
Hey, you stupid jerk!

622
00:37:32,647 --> 00:37:34,408
I'm singing a song here.

623
00:37:37,483 --> 00:37:38,915
Polly, get out here!

624
00:37:38,983 --> 00:37:41,415
Shut up yourself!

625
00:37:41,484 --> 00:37:42,951
Just shut up!

626
00:37:45,519 --> 00:37:48,454
Forrest! What are you
doing here?

627
00:37:48,521 --> 00:37:49,852
What are you doing?

628
00:37:49,922 --> 00:37:50,853
- Hey!
- Aw!

629
00:37:50,922 --> 00:37:52,684
What are you doing, Forrest?

630
00:37:52,757 --> 00:37:54,782
Let me down!

631
00:37:54,859 --> 00:37:57,382
- Oh! Ooh!
- Ooh!

632
00:37:57,459 --> 00:37:58,861
Ha ha ha!

633
00:37:58,994 --> 00:38:01,427
You can't keep
doing this, Forrest.

634
00:38:01,495 --> 00:38:03,927
You can't keep
trying to rescue me.

635
00:38:03,996 --> 00:38:05,793
They was trying to grab you.

636
00:38:05,865 --> 00:38:08,195
A lot of people try to grab me.

637
00:38:08,265 --> 00:38:12,257
Just... You can't keep
doing this all the time.

638
00:38:12,335 --> 00:38:15,860
I can't help it.
I love you.

639
00:38:15,936 --> 00:38:18,199
Forrest...

640
00:38:18,271 --> 00:38:20,238
You don't know what love is.

641
00:38:26,976 --> 00:38:29,910
You remember that time
we prayed, Forrest?

642
00:38:31,311 --> 00:38:34,746
We prayed for God
to turn me into a bird

643
00:38:34,814 --> 00:38:36,746
so I could fly far away.

644
00:38:37,982 --> 00:38:39,573
Yes, I do.

645
00:38:42,551 --> 00:38:44,984
You think I could
fly off this bridge?

646
00:38:52,223 --> 00:38:55,247
What do you mean, Jenny?

647
00:38:58,426 --> 00:38:59,687
Nothing.

648
00:39:02,762 --> 00:39:05,024
I got to get out of here.

649
00:39:07,265 --> 00:39:08,357
Wait, Jenny.

650
00:39:08,432 --> 00:39:10,864
Forrest, you stay
away from me, O.K.?

651
00:39:10,933 --> 00:39:12,866
You stay away from me, please.

652
00:39:12,934 --> 00:39:14,367
Can I have a ride?

653
00:39:14,435 --> 00:39:15,697
Where are you going?

654
00:39:15,770 --> 00:39:16,860
I don't care.

655
00:39:16,936 --> 00:39:18,164
Get in the truck.

656
00:39:18,237 --> 00:39:20,431
So bye-bye, Jenny.

657
00:39:21,839 --> 00:39:24,705
They sending me to Vietnam.

658
00:39:26,409 --> 00:39:29,240
It's this whole other country.

659
00:39:31,811 --> 00:39:33,573
Just hang on a minute.

660
00:39:35,146 --> 00:39:38,080
Listen, you promise me
something, O.K.?

661
00:39:38,148 --> 00:39:40,081
Just if you're ever in trouble,

662
00:39:40,149 --> 00:39:41,411
don't be brave.

663
00:39:41,483 --> 00:39:44,418
You just run, O.K.?
Just run away.

664
00:39:44,486 --> 00:39:45,849
O.K.

665
00:39:50,588 --> 00:39:52,351
Jenny.

666
00:39:53,924 --> 00:39:57,016
I'll write you all the time.

667
00:40:05,597 --> 00:40:09,193
<i>And just like that,
she was gone.</i>

668
00:40:24,440 --> 00:40:26,873
You come back safe to me.

669
00:40:26,941 --> 00:40:28,374
Do you hear?

670
00:40:47,952 --> 00:40:49,544
~ Some folks are born ~

671
00:40:49,620 --> 00:40:51,883
~ Made to wave the flag ~

672
00:40:51,955 --> 00:40:55,218
~ Ooh, they're red,
white, and blue ~

673
00:40:55,290 --> 00:40:58,815
~ And when the band plays
"Hail To The Chief" ~

674
00:40:58,891 --> 00:41:02,485
~ Ooh, they'll point
the cannon at you ~

675
00:41:02,561 --> 00:41:06,328
~ it ain't me ~

676
00:41:06,396 --> 00:41:09,489
~ I ain't no senator's son ~

677
00:41:09,565 --> 00:41:11,327
~ it ain't me ~

678
00:41:11,399 --> 00:41:12,831
<i>Now they told us</i>

679
00:41:12,899 --> 00:41:15,833
<i>that Vietnam was going
to be very different</i>

680
00:41:15,901 --> 00:41:17,925
<i>from the United States
of America.</i>

681
00:41:18,002 --> 00:41:22,096
<i>Except for all
the beer cans and barbecues,</i>

682
00:41:22,171 --> 00:41:23,933
<i>it was.</i>

683
00:41:33,678 --> 00:41:36,771
Hey, I'll bet there's shrimp
all in these waters.

684
00:41:36,847 --> 00:41:39,780
They tell me these Vietnams
is good shrimp.

685
00:41:39,848 --> 00:41:41,781
After we win this war

686
00:41:41,849 --> 00:41:43,476
and we take over everything,

687
00:41:43,550 --> 00:41:45,812
we can get American
shrimpers out here

688
00:41:45,884 --> 00:41:47,146
and shrimp these waters.

689
00:41:47,219 --> 00:41:49,152
Just shrimp all the time, man.

690
00:41:51,888 --> 00:41:54,151
You must be my FNGs.

691
00:41:54,223 --> 00:41:55,315
Morning, sir.

692
00:41:55,389 --> 00:41:56,912
Oh, get your hands down.

693
00:41:56,990 --> 00:41:58,423
Do not salute me.

694
00:41:58,492 --> 00:42:00,925
There are goddamn snipers
all around this area

695
00:42:00,993 --> 00:42:03,085
who'd love
to grease an officer.

696
00:42:03,161 --> 00:42:06,425
I'm Lieutenant Dan Taylor.
Welcome to Fort Platoon.

697
00:42:07,662 --> 00:42:09,254
What's wrong with your lip?

698
00:42:10,332 --> 00:42:12,594
I was born with big gums, sir.

699
00:42:12,665 --> 00:42:14,757
Well, you better tuck that in.

700
00:42:14,833 --> 00:42:17,267
Gonna get that caught
on a trip wire.

701
00:42:18,502 --> 00:42:20,936
Where are you boys
from in the world?

702
00:42:21,004 --> 00:42:22,095
- Alabama, sir!
- Alabama, sir!

703
00:42:23,339 --> 00:42:24,305
You twins?

704
00:42:26,540 --> 00:42:29,133
No. We are not relations, sir.

705
00:42:31,209 --> 00:42:32,471
Look,

706
00:42:32,544 --> 00:42:33,874
it's pretty basic here.

707
00:42:34,945 --> 00:42:36,206
You stick with me

708
00:42:36,279 --> 00:42:37,711
and learn from the guys

709
00:42:37,779 --> 00:42:39,713
who've been in country a while,

710
00:42:39,781 --> 00:42:41,041
you'll be all right.

711
00:42:41,114 --> 00:42:43,378
There is one item of G.I. Gear

712
00:42:43,450 --> 00:42:46,543
that can be the difference
between life and death...

713
00:42:46,618 --> 00:42:47,675
Socks.

714
00:42:47,751 --> 00:42:49,776
Cushioned sole, O.D. Green.

715
00:42:49,853 --> 00:42:51,683
Try and keep your feet dry.

716
00:42:51,754 --> 00:42:54,187
When we're out humpin',
change your socks

717
00:42:54,256 --> 00:42:55,449
whenever we stop.

718
00:42:55,523 --> 00:42:57,787
The Mekong will eat
a grunt's feet

719
00:42:57,858 --> 00:42:59,289
right off his legs.

720
00:42:59,358 --> 00:43:00,791
Sergeant Sims. God damn it,

721
00:43:00,859 --> 00:43:03,292
where's that sling rope
I said to order?

722
00:43:03,361 --> 00:43:04,793
I put in the requisitions.

723
00:43:04,861 --> 00:43:07,124
Well, you call
those sons of bitches...

724
00:43:07,196 --> 00:43:09,288
<i>Lieutenant Dan
sure knew his stuff.</i>

725
00:43:09,363 --> 00:43:12,298
<i>I felt real lucky
he was my lieutenant.</i>

726
00:43:12,366 --> 00:43:16,027
<i>He was from a long,
great military tradition.</i>

727
00:43:16,101 --> 00:43:18,625
<i>Somebody in his family
had fought</i>

728
00:43:18,702 --> 00:43:20,168
<i>and died</i>

729
00:43:20,236 --> 00:43:21,827
<i>in every...</i>

730
00:43:21,904 --> 00:43:23,030
<i>single...</i>

731
00:43:23,105 --> 00:43:25,197
<i>American war.</i>

732
00:43:25,273 --> 00:43:27,206
God damn it, kick some ass.

733
00:43:27,274 --> 00:43:28,535
Get on it!

734
00:43:28,607 --> 00:43:30,040
<i>I guess you could say</i>

735
00:43:30,109 --> 00:43:32,541
<i>he had a lot to live up to.</i>

736
00:43:33,610 --> 00:43:35,543
So, you boys
from Arkansas, huh?

737
00:43:35,611 --> 00:43:36,703
Well,

738
00:43:36,779 --> 00:43:38,540
I been through there.

739
00:43:38,612 --> 00:43:41,376
Little Rock's a fine town.

740
00:43:41,448 --> 00:43:43,210
Now, shake down your gear.

741
00:43:43,283 --> 00:43:44,544
See the platoon sergeant.

742
00:43:44,616 --> 00:43:47,379
Draw what you need
for the field.

743
00:43:47,451 --> 00:43:48,884
If you boys are hungry,

744
00:43:48,953 --> 00:43:51,715
we got steaks burning
right over here.

745
00:43:51,787 --> 00:43:54,550
Two standing orders
in this platoon...

746
00:43:54,622 --> 00:43:57,145
1... take care of your feet,

747
00:43:57,223 --> 00:44:00,816
2... try not to do
anything stupid,

748
00:44:00,891 --> 00:44:02,483
like getting yourself killed.

749
00:44:08,729 --> 00:44:11,253
I sure hope I don't
let him down.

750
00:44:22,437 --> 00:44:25,371
<i>I got to see
a lot of the countryside.</i>

751
00:44:25,439 --> 00:44:27,838
<i>We would take
these real long walks.</i>

752
00:44:29,907 --> 00:44:31,841
~ There must be
some kind of way ~

753
00:44:31,909 --> 00:44:34,001
~ Out of here ~

754
00:44:34,077 --> 00:44:36,169
~ Said the joker to the thief ~

755
00:44:36,245 --> 00:44:37,677
<i>And we were always lookin'</i>

756
00:44:37,745 --> 00:44:39,679
<i>for this guy named Charlie.</i>

757
00:44:39,747 --> 00:44:41,337
~ There's too much confusion ~

758
00:44:42,748 --> 00:44:45,511
~ I can't get no relief ~

759
00:44:48,084 --> 00:44:49,176
Hold it up!

760
00:44:49,252 --> 00:44:50,685
Hold up, boys!

761
00:44:52,253 --> 00:44:55,278
<i>It wasn't always fun.</i>

762
00:44:55,355 --> 00:44:58,618
<i>Lieutenant Dan was always
getting these funny feelings</i>

763
00:44:58,690 --> 00:45:01,784
<i>about a rock or a trail
or the road,</i>

764
00:45:01,859 --> 00:45:04,792
<i>so he'd tell us
to get down, shut up.</i>

765
00:45:04,860 --> 00:45:05,951
Get down!

766
00:45:06,027 --> 00:45:07,119
Shut up!

767
00:45:08,196 --> 00:45:09,456
<i>So we did.</i>

768
00:45:25,972 --> 00:45:29,236
<i>Now I don't know
much about anything,</i>

769
00:45:29,307 --> 00:45:32,240
<i>but I think some of
America's best young men</i>

770
00:45:32,308 --> 00:45:33,570
<i>served in this war.</i>

771
00:45:33,643 --> 00:45:35,906
<i>There was Dallas from Phoenix.</i>

772
00:45:37,311 --> 00:45:40,074
<i>Cleveland...
he was from Detroit.</i>

773
00:45:40,146 --> 00:45:42,936
Hey, Tex.

774
00:45:43,014 --> 00:45:44,606
What the hell's going on?

775
00:45:44,682 --> 00:45:46,876
<i>And Tex was...</i>

776
00:45:46,950 --> 00:45:49,542
<i>Well, I don't remember
where Tex come from...</i>

777
00:45:49,618 --> 00:45:51,142
Ah, nothing.

778
00:45:55,054 --> 00:45:57,078
Fourth platoon, on your feet.

779
00:45:57,155 --> 00:46:00,055
Y'all got 10 clicks
to go to that river.

780
00:46:00,124 --> 00:46:01,715
Move out.

781
00:46:01,791 --> 00:46:04,224
1, 2! Hup!

782
00:46:05,627 --> 00:46:07,060
Step it up!

783
00:46:07,128 --> 00:46:08,458
Look alive out there.

784
00:46:08,528 --> 00:46:09,961
<i>The good thing about Vietnam</i>

785
00:46:10,030 --> 00:46:12,292
<i>is there was always
someplace to go.</i>

786
00:46:12,364 --> 00:46:13,626
Fire in the hole!

787
00:46:17,200 --> 00:46:19,793
Gump, check out that hole.

788
00:46:19,868 --> 00:46:22,801
<i>And there was always
something to do.</i>

789
00:46:22,869 --> 00:46:23,961
Mount 'em up!

790
00:46:24,037 --> 00:46:25,834
Spread out!
Cover his back!

791
00:46:30,907 --> 00:46:33,500
<i>One day it started raining,</i>

792
00:46:33,576 --> 00:46:36,907
<i>and it didn't quit for four months.</i>

793
00:46:36,977 --> 00:46:40,412
<i>We've been through
every kind of rain there is...</i>

794
00:46:40,480 --> 00:46:43,107
<i>little bitty stinging rain</i>

795
00:46:43,181 --> 00:46:47,081
<i>and big old fat rain,</i>

796
00:46:47,150 --> 00:46:49,950
<i>rain that flew in sideways,</i>

797
00:46:50,083 --> 00:46:51,742
<i>and sometimes rain even seemed</i>

798
00:46:51,816 --> 00:46:55,148
<i>to come straight up
from underneath.</i>

799
00:46:55,218 --> 00:46:58,743
<i>Shoot, it even rained at night.</i>

800
00:46:58,820 --> 00:47:00,583
Hey, Forrest.

801
00:47:00,655 --> 00:47:01,747
Hey, Bubba.

802
00:47:01,823 --> 00:47:04,085
I'm going to lean up against you.

803
00:47:04,157 --> 00:47:05,590
You lean up against me.

804
00:47:05,658 --> 00:47:07,921
This way we don't have to sleep

805
00:47:07,993 --> 00:47:09,925
with our heads in the mud.

806
00:47:09,993 --> 00:47:12,587
You know why we're
a good partnership, Forrest?

807
00:47:12,662 --> 00:47:15,925
'Cause we be watching out
for one another,

808
00:47:15,997 --> 00:47:17,759
like brothers and stuff.

809
00:47:19,665 --> 00:47:21,256
Hey, Forrest,

810
00:47:21,333 --> 00:47:23,426
something I been thinking about.

811
00:47:23,501 --> 00:47:26,434
I got a very important
question to ask you.

812
00:47:28,170 --> 00:47:30,104
How would you like to go

813
00:47:30,172 --> 00:47:32,104
into the shrimping
business with me?

814
00:47:33,673 --> 00:47:34,935
O.K.

815
00:47:35,008 --> 00:47:36,769
Man, I tell you what.

816
00:47:36,841 --> 00:47:39,104
I got it all figured out, too.

817
00:47:39,176 --> 00:47:40,609
So many pounds of shrimp

818
00:47:40,677 --> 00:47:42,110
will pay off the boat.

819
00:47:42,179 --> 00:47:43,610
So many pounds for gas.

820
00:47:43,678 --> 00:47:45,612
We'll live right on the boat.

821
00:47:45,680 --> 00:47:47,943
We ain't got to pay no rent.

822
00:47:48,014 --> 00:47:49,947
We can just work it together,

823
00:47:50,015 --> 00:47:51,949
split everything right
down the middle.

824
00:47:52,017 --> 00:47:54,108
Man, I'm telling you, 50-50.

825
00:47:54,184 --> 00:47:57,209
Hey, Forrest,
all the shrimp you can eat.

826
00:47:58,787 --> 00:48:01,379
That's a fine idea.

827
00:48:01,455 --> 00:48:04,219
<i>Bubba did have a fine idea.</i>

828
00:48:07,625 --> 00:48:08,886
<i>I even wrote Jenny</i>

829
00:48:08,959 --> 00:48:10,892
<i>and told her all about it.</i>

830
00:48:10,960 --> 00:48:12,551
<i>I sent her letters...</i>

831
00:48:12,627 --> 00:48:14,720
<i>Not every day, but almost.</i>

832
00:48:14,796 --> 00:48:17,058
<i>I told her what I was doing</i>

833
00:48:17,130 --> 00:48:19,563
<i>and asked her what she was doing</i>

834
00:48:19,631 --> 00:48:22,865
<i>and told her how
I thought about her always.</i>

835
00:48:24,233 --> 00:48:26,166
<i>And how I was looking forward</i>

836
00:48:26,234 --> 00:48:28,167
<i>to getting a letter from her</i>

837
00:48:28,235 --> 00:48:30,998
<i>just as soon
as she had the time.</i>

838
00:48:31,070 --> 00:48:34,003
<i>I'd always let her know
that I was O.K.</i>

839
00:48:34,071 --> 00:48:41,497
<i>Then I'd sign each letter
"Love, Forrest Gump."</i>

840
00:48:51,414 --> 00:48:54,177
~ There's somethin'
happenin' here ~

841
00:48:55,516 --> 00:48:59,109
<i>This one day, we was out
walking like always,</i>

842
00:48:59,185 --> 00:49:02,949
<i>and then, just like that,</i>

843
00:49:03,020 --> 00:49:04,954
<i>somebody turned off the rain,</i>

844
00:49:05,022 --> 00:49:06,613
<i>and the sun come out.</i>

845
00:49:06,689 --> 00:49:09,452
~ I got to beware ~

846
00:49:09,524 --> 00:49:11,616
Ambush!

847
00:49:11,692 --> 00:49:13,624
Take cover!

848
00:49:22,198 --> 00:49:24,865
Get that pig up here,
god damn it!

849
00:49:24,998 --> 00:49:27,125
Forrest! You okay?

850
00:49:29,735 --> 00:49:32,634
Strong-arm, Strong-arm!

851
00:49:32,703 --> 00:49:35,500
Hey! We got a man down!

852
00:49:35,571 --> 00:49:39,028
Strong-arm,
this is Leg Lima 6! Over!

853
00:49:39,106 --> 00:49:41,540
Roger, Strong-arm!
Be advised we have incoming

854
00:49:41,609 --> 00:49:44,007
from the treeline at point blue

855
00:49:44,076 --> 00:49:46,407
plus two!
A.K.S and rockets!

856
00:49:46,477 --> 00:49:47,738
We're getting it hard!

857
00:49:47,811 --> 00:49:49,369
Misfire! Misfire!

858
00:49:50,446 --> 00:49:52,243
God damn it!

859
00:49:53,814 --> 00:49:57,749
Get that pig unfucked
and on the treeline!

860
00:49:59,584 --> 00:50:02,177
They got us, and it hurt.

861
00:50:02,253 --> 00:50:05,743
We're going to move
back to the blue line.

862
00:50:05,821 --> 00:50:08,721
Pull back! Pull back!

863
00:50:08,789 --> 00:50:10,779
Forrest! Run, Forrest!

864
00:50:10,857 --> 00:50:12,585
Pull back!

865
00:50:12,658 --> 00:50:14,853
Run! Run, man!

866
00:50:14,927 --> 00:50:16,017
Run!

867
00:50:16,093 --> 00:50:17,355
Pull back, Gump!

868
00:50:18,929 --> 00:50:22,090
Run, God damn it! Run!

869
00:50:48,012 --> 00:50:52,036
<i>I ran and ran
just like Jenny told me to.</i>

870
00:50:54,782 --> 00:50:56,975
<i>I ran so far so fast</i>

871
00:50:57,049 --> 00:50:59,482
<i>that pretty soon
I was all by myself,</i>

872
00:50:59,550 --> 00:51:01,142
<i>which was a bad thing.</i>

873
00:51:01,219 --> 00:51:02,310
Bubba.

874
00:51:04,887 --> 00:51:06,979
<i>Bubba was my best good friend.</i>

875
00:51:07,055 --> 00:51:09,488
<i>I had to make sure he was O.K.</i>

876
00:51:18,560 --> 00:51:20,994
Where the hell are you?

877
00:51:21,063 --> 00:51:23,155
Bubba!

878
00:51:23,231 --> 00:51:26,164
<i>And on my way
back to find Bubba,</i>

879
00:51:26,232 --> 00:51:28,995
<i>well, there was this boy
laying on the ground.</i>

880
00:51:29,067 --> 00:51:30,055
Tex.

881
00:51:32,001 --> 00:51:33,593
O.K.

882
00:51:33,670 --> 00:51:36,102
<i>I couldn't let him
lay there all alone,</i>

883
00:51:36,170 --> 00:51:37,603
<i>scared the way he was,</i>

884
00:51:37,672 --> 00:51:39,434
<i>so I grabbed him up</i>

885
00:51:39,506 --> 00:51:41,234
<i>and run him out of there.</i>

886
00:51:56,449 --> 00:51:59,177
<i>Every time I went back
looking for Bubba,</i>

887
00:51:59,250 --> 00:52:00,683
<i>somebody else was saying,</i>

888
00:52:00,751 --> 00:52:03,685
<i>"Help me, Forrest, help me!"</i>

889
00:52:10,256 --> 00:52:12,435
O.K. Here. Here.

890
00:52:14,764 --> 00:52:17,756
No sweat, man.
Lay back. You'll be O.K.

891
00:52:20,179 --> 00:52:24,674
<i>I started to get scared
that I might never find Bubba.</i>

892
00:52:24,753 --> 00:52:26,198
I know my position

893
00:52:26,266 --> 00:52:28,181
is danger close!

894
00:52:28,250 --> 00:52:30,704
We got Charlie
all over this area.

895
00:52:30,773 --> 00:52:33,731
I got to have those fast movers
in here now. Over.

896
00:52:33,799 --> 00:52:36,253
Lieutenant Dan, Coleman's dead!

897
00:52:36,323 --> 00:52:37,768
I know he's dead!

898
00:52:37,836 --> 00:52:40,794
My whole goddamn platoon
is wiped out!

899
00:52:40,863 --> 00:52:42,308
God damn it!

900
00:52:42,377 --> 00:52:44,326
What are you doing?

901
00:52:44,395 --> 00:52:45,839
You leave me here!

902
00:52:45,908 --> 00:52:47,858
Get away.
Just leave me here!

903
00:52:47,926 --> 00:52:49,371
Get out!

904
00:52:49,441 --> 00:52:53,408
Aah! God, I said
leave me here, God damn it!

905
00:52:53,476 --> 00:52:55,861
<i>Leg Lima, this is Strong-arm.</i>

906
00:52:55,931 --> 00:52:58,925
<i>Be advised your fast movers
are inbound. Over.</i>

907
00:52:58,992 --> 00:53:02,420
<i>Then it felt like something
just jumped up and bit me.</i>

908
00:53:02,490 --> 00:53:05,276
Aah! Something bit me!

909
00:53:09,049 --> 00:53:12,168
Aah! Aah!

910
00:53:12,244 --> 00:53:14,194
You son of a bitch!

911
00:53:14,263 --> 00:53:15,604
Aah!

912
00:53:15,675 --> 00:53:18,699
I can't leave the platoon.

913
00:53:18,776 --> 00:53:21,711
I told you
to leave me there, Gump.

914
00:53:21,779 --> 00:53:23,745
Forget about me.
Get yourself out!

915
00:53:23,812 --> 00:53:26,042
Did you hear what I said?

916
00:53:26,115 --> 00:53:28,548
Gump, damn it, put me down.

917
00:53:28,616 --> 00:53:31,140
Get your ass out of here.

918
00:53:33,119 --> 00:53:36,245
I didn't ask you to pull me out
of there, God damn you!

919
00:53:36,320 --> 00:53:39,255
Where the hell
do you think you're going?

920
00:53:39,323 --> 00:53:40,754
To get Bubba.

921
00:53:40,822 --> 00:53:43,757
I got an air strike
inbound right now.

922
00:53:43,825 --> 00:53:46,315
They're going to nape
the whole area.

923
00:53:46,393 --> 00:53:47,860
Stay here!
That's an order.

924
00:53:47,928 --> 00:53:49,361
I gotta find Bubba!

925
00:54:04,571 --> 00:54:06,266
Forrest.

926
00:54:13,577 --> 00:54:14,907
Bubba.

927
00:54:14,977 --> 00:54:16,807
I'm O.K., Forrest.

928
00:54:16,878 --> 00:54:18,402
I'm O.K.

929
00:54:26,817 --> 00:54:28,842
O-Oh, Bubba, no.

930
00:54:28,919 --> 00:54:30,715
I'll be all right.

931
00:54:39,092 --> 00:54:40,183
Come on.

932
00:54:40,259 --> 00:54:41,988
Come on. Come on.

933
00:54:45,963 --> 00:54:48,658
Ugh. I'm O.K., Forrest.

934
00:54:51,600 --> 00:54:53,533
I'm O.K. I'm fine.

935
00:55:30,022 --> 00:55:33,048
Top smoke. Get it up there.

936
00:55:33,125 --> 00:55:35,990
<i>If I'd have known
this was going to be</i>

937
00:55:36,059 --> 00:55:38,993
<i>the last time
me and Bubba was gonna talk,</i>

938
00:55:39,061 --> 00:55:41,995
<i>I'd of thought of
something better to say.</i>

939
00:55:42,063 --> 00:55:43,120
Hey, Bubba.

940
00:55:43,197 --> 00:55:44,459
Hey, Forrest.

941
00:55:46,898 --> 00:55:48,331
Forrest...

942
00:55:48,400 --> 00:55:51,492
Why did this happen?

943
00:55:51,568 --> 00:55:54,503
You got shot.

944
00:55:54,571 --> 00:55:58,938
<i>Then Bubba said something
I won't ever forget.</i>

945
00:55:59,007 --> 00:56:02,567
I want to go home.

946
00:56:02,643 --> 00:56:05,439
<i>Bubba was my best good friend.</i>

947
00:56:05,510 --> 00:56:07,444
<i>And even I know</i>

948
00:56:07,512 --> 00:56:10,946
<i>that ain't something you can
find just around the corner.</i>

949
00:56:11,014 --> 00:56:14,448
<i>Bubba was going to be
a shrimping boat captain,</i>

950
00:56:14,515 --> 00:56:18,814
<i>but instead, he died right there
by that river in Vietnam.</i>

951
00:56:24,389 --> 00:56:26,720
That's all I have
to say about that.

952
00:56:28,924 --> 00:56:31,119
It was a bullet, wasn't it?

953
00:56:33,027 --> 00:56:34,460
A bullet?

954
00:56:34,528 --> 00:56:37,256
That jumped up and bit you.

955
00:56:38,397 --> 00:56:40,262
Oh. Yes, sir.

956
00:56:40,332 --> 00:56:42,958
Bit me directly
in the but-tocks.

957
00:56:43,033 --> 00:56:47,469
They said it was a million
dollar wound, but...

958
00:56:47,536 --> 00:56:49,469
The army must keep that money,

959
00:56:49,537 --> 00:56:53,472
'cause I still ain't seen a nickel
of that million dollars.

960
00:56:53,540 --> 00:56:57,341
The only good thing about being
wounded in the but-tocks

961
00:56:57,474 --> 00:56:59,236
<i>is the ice cream.</i>

962
00:56:59,308 --> 00:57:02,208
<i>They gave me all
the ice cream I could eat.</i>

963
00:57:02,277 --> 00:57:03,709
<i>And guess what?</i>

964
00:57:03,777 --> 00:57:07,678
<i>A good friend of mine was
in the bed right next door.</i>

965
00:57:08,980 --> 00:57:12,039
Lieutenant Dan,
I got you some ice cream.

966
00:57:13,917 --> 00:57:16,647
Lieutenant Dan, ice cream!

967
00:57:27,492 --> 00:57:30,255
It's time for
your bath, Lieutenant.

968
00:57:38,499 --> 00:57:39,896
Harper!

969
00:57:43,502 --> 00:57:44,934
Cooper.

970
00:57:45,002 --> 00:57:45,933
Larson.

971
00:57:48,004 --> 00:57:49,265
Webster.

972
00:57:50,506 --> 00:57:51,938
Gump.

973
00:57:52,006 --> 00:57:53,438
Gump!

974
00:57:53,507 --> 00:57:55,134
I'm Forrest Gump.

975
00:57:57,443 --> 00:57:58,841
Kyle.

976
00:58:00,445 --> 00:58:01,776
Nichols.

977
00:58:03,513 --> 00:58:05,879
McMill.

978
00:58:05,949 --> 00:58:06,937
Johnson.

979
00:58:18,055 --> 00:58:21,022
<i>Surprise, surprise, surprise!</i>

980
00:58:23,825 --> 00:58:27,259
Gump, how can you
watch that stupid shit?

981
00:58:27,327 --> 00:58:28,760
Turn it off.

982
00:58:28,828 --> 00:58:31,260
<i>You are tuned
to the American forces</i>

983
00:58:31,329 --> 00:58:32,762
<i>Vietnam network.</i>

984
00:58:32,830 --> 00:58:34,387
<i>This is channel 6, Saigon.</i>

985
00:58:36,832 --> 00:58:38,492
Good catch, Gump.

986
00:58:40,335 --> 00:58:42,234
You know how to play this?

987
00:58:43,836 --> 00:58:46,304
Come on. Let me show you.

988
00:58:47,838 --> 00:58:50,272
Now, the secret to this game is

989
00:58:50,341 --> 00:58:52,274
no matter what happens,

990
00:58:52,342 --> 00:58:54,775
never, ever...

991
00:58:54,843 --> 00:58:56,935
Take your eye off the ball.

992
00:58:59,846 --> 00:59:01,107
All right.

993
00:59:04,350 --> 00:59:05,781
<i>For some reason,</i>

994
00:59:05,849 --> 00:59:08,283
<i>Ping-Pong came very natural to me.</i>

995
00:59:08,352 --> 00:59:09,512
See?

996
00:59:09,586 --> 00:59:11,779
Any idiot can play.

997
00:59:11,853 --> 00:59:15,288
<i>So I started playing it
all the time.</i>

998
00:59:15,356 --> 00:59:16,982
<i>I played Ping-Pong</i>

999
00:59:17,057 --> 00:59:20,651
<i>even when I didn't have anyone
to play Ping-Pong with.</i>

1000
00:59:28,997 --> 00:59:30,430
<i>The hospital's people</i>

1001
00:59:30,498 --> 00:59:34,432
<i>said it made me look
like a duck in water...</i>

1002
00:59:34,500 --> 00:59:35,933
<i>Whatever that means.</i>

1003
00:59:36,002 --> 00:59:39,231
<i>Even Lieutenant Dan
would come and watch me play.</i>

1004
00:59:44,006 --> 00:59:46,438
<i>I played Ping-Pong so much,</i>

1005
00:59:46,506 --> 00:59:49,339
<i>I even played it in my sleep.</i>

1006
00:59:56,445 --> 00:59:57,377
Now...

1007
00:59:57,446 --> 00:59:58,879
